ships between the state and its citizens, enabling a collective disavowal of colonial violence. In Sovereign Intimacy, Melamed offers a poignant and critical view of the weaponization of home media and mourning in service of the neoliberal settler state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBereavementxPolitical aspectszIsraely20th century. 0aSocial mediazIsraely20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 2023 Englishz978311131909408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 2023z978311131812708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079134140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520390317?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520390317423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520390317/original  a978-3-11-079134-1  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-131812-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 2023b2023  a978-3-11-131909-4  EBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-131929-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishb2023  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2023